<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-09-05T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-09-05T23:00:00-05:00" n="315" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d315">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/5496: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bell</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-09-06T12:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">September 6,
                                        1924—noon</hi></date>.<lb/>[Received September 6—8:15
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>325. My 318, September 2, 5 p.m., last paragraph. Naval attaché returned
                            yesterday from Harbin and Mukden, reports after careful inspection he
                            could find no evidence of Marshal Chang Tso-lin intending to move in
                            immediate future. His attitude appeared to be one of watchful
                            waiting.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Bell</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>